44. The strongest influence in producing differences between the prosody of Plautus and that of Horace and Vergil was exerted by the accent. The Latin usage which tended to fix the accent upon the penult or antepenult‚ with- drew from the ultima a preservative force, and expedited the shortening and dropping off oi inflectional endings. This process went on during the whole history oi the language‚ but it was much more rapid and extended in the spoken than in the written Latin. For this reason, though he preceded Vergil by a century and a hali, Plautus has many more cases ol syllables shortened by the accent than any Augustan poet.
